<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: JOE CAMEL VS. THE MARLBORO MAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Across the country, Joe Camel is apparently bursting through billboards 
advertising his biggest rival, the Marlboro Man. 
</P>
<P>
 Joe Camel peers over an image of a cowboy on horseback and holds out a pack of 
Camel Lights. The tag line reads: "Genuine Taste, Never Boring." 
</P>
<P>
 R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. thought the time was right to go after Marlboro 
smokers, said Peggy Carter, a spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
 At the end of the fiscal second quarter, Marlboro had 28.8% of the estimated 
$48-billion U.S. cigarette market. Camel had about 3.8% of the market. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're saying, 'Hey, competitive smoker, we're talking to you,' in that fun 
and irreverent vein that is Joe Camel's style," Carter said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
